# 48_proj_new_smoke — fifth and final File-menu verb on the proj
# headless-verb singleton (s250 m1). Closes the m5b proj-surface arc
# at 5 of 5 File-menu items (save / save_as / close / load / new).
# Third verb under the surface-preservation rule articulated by
# s248 m1 (close was the first, load was the second); third live
# exercise of curvz::scripting::path_is_safe under user-supplied
# input (save_as was the first, load was the second).
#
# Tier 4 row remains at 1/~4-5: same singleton, fifth verb; no tick.
# Surface widening: proj verb count 4 → 5. Query count unchanged.
# m5b proj-surface arc CLOSES at this milestone — all five File-menu
# verbs are now addressable.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Scripter context refuses new at the dispatcher BEFORE the verb's
# body runs. new is declared as ctx::TestRunner only in
# ProjScriptable::context_mask — by the surface-preservation rule
# (new destroys any currently-loaded project AND seeds a fresh empty
# one in its place; either half alone would justify TestRunner-only).
# Same dispatcher layer as smokes 45 (save_as), 46 (close), and 47
# (load) refuse their respective verbs.
#
# What this smoke CAN observe from Scripter:
#
#   - Every new call refuses with the standard RunContext refusal
#     message, regardless of the path argument. The path-safety
#     check, the dirty check, and the target-exists check wired
#     inside the verb body are all structurally unreachable from
#     Scripter (the gate fires first). Same pattern as smokes 45
#     and 47 for save_as and load respectively.
#
#   - The project's path is unchanged after every refused call. The
#     RunContext gate is a structured early-return; no state mutation
#     happens. The `proj has_path` and `proj path` queries before and
#     after each refusal are the assertable observable.
#
# What this smoke CANNOT observe from Scripter:
#
#   - path_is_safe's accept/refuse split as exercised through the
#     new verb body. The verb body is wired with the path-safety
#     pre-flight live (any TestRunner caller will exercise it), but
#     from this caller the body never runs. Live path_is_safe
#     coverage for new waits for the future CLI test runner. Same
#     coverage-deferral note as smokes 45 and 47.
#
#   - The dirty refusal (script_new_project's structurally stricter
#     posture than on_new_project's check_unsaved_then-modal-driven
#     prompt). The script-side new refuses on can_undo() == true
#     rather than summoning a modal; from Scripter context the
#     dispatcher refuses first, so this branch is unreachable here
#     too. Logged for when the test runner lands.
#
#   - The TargetExists refusal — NEW in s250 m1 and structurally
#     distinct from anything load has. new refuses when
#     fs::exists(path) is true BEFORE create_empty runs, stricter
#     than the GUI's on_new_project which silently overwrites. This
#     is the most interesting refusal to land under a TestRunner
#     analogue: it's the one refusal that's truly unique to new (vs.
#     load) and the one that catches the most surprising
#     destructive-script case (typo against an established
#     directory). Logged explicitly for when the test runner lands;
#     the analogue should assert TargetExists-then-refuse as a
#     distinct error shape from the Dirty refusal.
#
#   - The CreateFailed refusal (create_empty returned null —
#     directory-creation or initial-save failed). Hard to exercise
#     even under TestRunner without filesystem fault injection.
#
# Three refuse cases are exercised below to demonstrate that the gate
# fires regardless of what path was supplied:
#
#   - A safe path that COULD be a fresh .curvz target under /tmp
#     (the path WOULD be accepted by path_is_safe if the body ran;
#     the gate refuses anyway; even if the gate were absent, the
#     helper would proceed to call CurvzProject::create_empty since
#     the path doesn't already exist — but the gate refuses upstream
#     of that).
#   - An unsafe path under /etc (the path WOULD be refused by
#     path_is_safe; the gate refuses first).
#   - An empty path (the path WOULD be refused by path_is_safe and
#     by the arg-validation guard; the gate refuses first).
#
# All three observable outcomes are identical from the dispatcher's
# perspective: same structured refusal line, no project mutation,
# no body execution. That uniformity IS the structural property
# the smoke confirms — same as smokes 45 and 47.
#
# ── Caller context ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context =
# RunContext::Scripter (set in ScripterWindow's ctor, see s244 m2
# wiring). new declares its mask as ctx::TestRunner only, so the
# dispatcher's context_allows check returns false on every new
# invoke from this caller.
#
# Sixth consumer of Scriptable::context_mask() in the codebase
# (Inspector + proj.save + proj.save_as + proj.close + proj.load +
# proj.new). Registry-promotion clock at 6/n; STILL HELD by design
# (s250 m1 decision — see ProjScriptable.hpp's context_mask block).
# The catalogue across this Scriptable is now markedly uniform:
# one verb at the Scripter | TestRunner mask (save), four verbs at
# the TestRunner-only mask (save_as, close, load, new). 80% mask
# uniformity strengthens the future-promotion argument but doesn't
# force it; the at-three reasoning (the virtual scales fine; central
# register_verb refactor's blast radius outweighs benefit until a
# typo bug bites) still holds at six.
#
# ── Test isolation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Fully non-destructive. Every new call refuses at the dispatcher
# gate before any state touches the project — m_project is not
# replaced, m_history is not reset, no panels are re-seeded, no
# config is rewritten, and crucially NO DIRECTORY IS CREATED on
# disk. The smoke does NOT write to disk — the
# /tmp/curvz_smoke_48_test.curvz path named below is never actually
# created because the gate refuses first. Repeatable without setup
# or teardown; safe to run against any project state Scott has
# loaded.
#
# Contrast with smoke 44 (proj save), which DOES write to disk —
# the dispatcher accepts `save` from Scripter (its mask includes
# Scripter), so the verb body runs and the project file's
# last-saved timestamp is refreshed. Smoke 48 does no such write
# (it doesn't even read from disk — the gate prevents both).

#[sub] === Phase 1: project state precondition ===

#[sub] Get the project's current directory path. Operator-visual:
#[sub] this should be the .curvz directory Scott has open right now.
#[sub] The has_path assertion below confirms the precondition for
#[sub] the post-refusal sanity checks (path unchanged after each
#[sub] refused call) — if has_path is false here, the sanity checks
#[sub] are meaningless because there's no path to be unchanged.
#[sub]
#[sub] Note that new — like load — is one of the project-lifecycle
#[sub] verbs where has_path == false would be a legitimate caller
#[sub] state (no project loaded yet, ready to create one). The
#[sub] smoke runs from a loaded-project state to ensure the
#[sub] post-refusal path-unchanged assertion is meaningful.

get proj path

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] === Phase 2: RunContext refusal — safe path ===

#[sub] Call new with a path that path_is_safe WOULD accept if the
#[sub] body ran (under /tmp, the canonical safe scratch location,
#[sub] AND a path that doesn't currently exist so the TargetExists
#[sub] check would also pass if the body ran). The expected trace
#[sub] line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   error invoke refused: verb 'new' on 'proj' not
#[sub]   permitted in scripter context
#[sub]
#[sub] Operator-visual on the refusal: read the line below this
#[sub] comment in the trace and confirm the structured refusal
#[sub] appears. The DSL's `assert` is equality-only on query
#[sub] results and can't directly compare against the listener's
#[sub] error line; same convention as smokes 45, 46, and 47.

proj new "/tmp/curvz_smoke_48_test.curvz"

#[sub] === Phase 3: post-refusal sanity (path unchanged) ===

#[sub] After the refused invoke, the project's directory is
#[sub] unchanged. The RunContext gate is a structured early-return
#[sub] (the verb body never ran), so no project replacement happened
#[sub] AND no directory was created on disk at the path supplied
#[sub] above. Same structural property smokes 45, 46, and 47
#[sub] confirmed for save_as, close, and load respectively: refusal
#[sub] means zero side effects.

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] === Phase 4: RunContext refusal — unsafe path ===

#[sub] Call new with a path that path_is_safe WOULD refuse if the
#[sub] body ran (under /etc, outside both $HOME and $TMPDIR). From
#[sub] Scripter context, the dispatcher refuses first — the
#[sub] path_is_safe check inside the verb body is never reached.
#[sub] Same refusal line text as Phase 2; the path argument doesn't
#[sub] affect the gate's decision.
#[sub]
#[sub] This is the structural property the smoke is here to confirm:
#[sub] the RunContext gate fires independent of path safety. Same
#[sub] property smokes 45 and 47 confirm for save_as and load.

proj new "/etc/curvz_smoke_48_test.curvz"

#[sub] === Phase 5: RunContext refusal — empty path ===

#[sub] Call new with an empty path. Same refusal at the gate; the
#[sub] verb body's argument-validation guard ("path argument is
#[sub] empty or not a string") is also unreached. Three different
#[sub] argument shapes, three identical structured refusals.

proj new ""

#[sub] === Phase 6: post-refusal sanity ===

#[sub] Final sanity assertion: the project's path is still unchanged
#[sub] after all three refusals. Confirms the dispatcher's
#[sub] refuse-without-touching-state contract held across multiple
#[sub] gate fires in a row.

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] s250 m1 smoke complete. Expected summary line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   7 lines, 3 pass, 0 fail, 3 error
#[sub]
#[sub] - 3 PASS  : has_path == true at Phases 1, 3, 6 (path unchanged
#[sub]             across the refusals)
#[sub] - 3 error : the three new RunContext refusals at Phases
#[sub]             2, 4, 5 (intentional — the gate working as
#[sub]             designed, one error per refused call per
#[sub]             ScriptListener's ++m_stats.errors at the gating
#[sub]             site)
#[sub] - 1 operator-visual : the `get proj path` echo at Phase 1
#[sub]             (shows which .curvz directory Scott has open)
#[sub] - 3 operator-visual refusals : the structured `error invoke
#[sub]             refused: verb 'new' on 'proj' not permitted in
#[sub]             scripter context` line under each refused new
#[sub]             call. Read in trace to confirm the refusal text
#[sub]             matches across all three.
#[sub]
#[sub] m5b proj-surface arc CLOSES at this milestone — all five
#[sub] File-menu verbs (save / save_as / close / load / new) are
#[sub] now script-addressable. Tier 4 row stays at 1/~4-5 (no tick
#[sub] — same singleton, fifth verb). Surface widening: `proj`
#[sub] Scriptable verb count goes 4 → 5; path_is_safe gains its
#[sub] third production call site (live in the verb body even if
#[sub] Scripter context never reaches it); context_mask() consumer
#[sub] count goes 5 → 6 (registry-promotion clock held at 6/n by
#[sub] design).

#[sub] ── Manual exercise for the verb body ──────────────────────
#[sub]
#[sub] To exercise the new verb body's accept and refuse paths
#[sub] (path_is_safe live, drag check, dirty check, target-exists
#[sub] check, CurvzProject::create_empty accept and refuse,
#[sub] load_project swap), the script needs to run under
#[sub] RunContext::TestRunner. No CLI test runner exists today;
#[sub] this is a backlog item.
#[sub]
#[sub] When the test runner lands, an analogue of this smoke will
#[sub] flip Phases 2/4/5 from operator-visual refusal observations
#[sub] to assertable accept/refuse observations on the resulting
#[sub] project path. Additional coverage worth queueing for the
#[sub] TestRunner analogue:
#[sub]
#[sub]   - Dirty refusal: new while can_undo() == true. The
#[sub]     stricter-than-GUI posture is structurally distinct from
#[sub]     on_new_project's check_unsaved_then modal flow and
#[sub]     worth asserting explicitly. (Different from load's
#[sub]     Dirty refusal in source — load's GUI counterpart
#[sub]     on_open MISSES check_unsaved_then entirely, which IS a
#[sub]     GUI bug; new's GUI counterpart on_new_project includes
#[sub]     it.)
#[sub]
#[sub]   - TargetExists refusal: new against a path that already
#[sub]     exists. This is the NEW refusal s250 m1 introduces — no
#[sub]     analogue in load, save, save_as, or close. The
#[sub]     test-runner analogue should set up an existing target
#[sub]     (mkdir or create a sentinel file) and assert that new
#[sub]     refuses without touching it. Critical coverage: the
#[sub]     GUI's silent-overwrite is the destruction surface this
#[sub]     refusal explicitly prevents.
#[sub]
#[sub]   - Ok: new to a legitimate, safe, not-yet-existing path
#[sub]     under /tmp. Post-create, `proj path` should match the
#[sub]     created path, `proj has_path` should be true, and the
#[sub]     directory should exist on disk with project.json,
#[sub]     swatches.json, styles.json, themes.json (from
#[sub]     seed_library_defaults). Teardown: rmdir the test
#[sub]     directory.
#[sub]
#[sub]   - CreateFailed: harder to exercise without filesystem
#[sub]     fault injection. Probably skipped until a use case
#[sub]     names the need.
